1. tuis litteris: in this letter, which has not been preserved, Cic- ero must have conveyed the impres- sion that he intended to join the Pompeians. —— nihil nisi triste: attributive acc. Cf. Intr. 83 ας see also Stinner, 58, n. 23 Becher, 31. — perscripsti ε for perscrip- sisti ; cf. praedixe for praedixisse, below. Cf. Intr. 82. —Ciceroz the earnestness of Caelius is shown by his use of the vocative Cicero twice in this letter. It occurs but once elsewhere in his letters.— oro obsecro: the use of such double expressions is especially common in colloquial language. The writer or speaker seeks to bring the idea home by coupling words or phrases which have essentially the same meaning.
